<DOCNO> AP900304-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a widely imitated environmental law banning 
plastic food containers and grocery bags was overturned by a state 
appeals court 
the suffolk county law intended to rid dumps of longlasting 
plastics was invalid because the county failed to prepare an 
environmental impact statement the appellate division of the state 
supreme court said in a unanimous ruling friday 
the law was hailed by environmentalists and became the model for 
measures around the country after it was passed in 1988 by the 
county on long island 
it banned restaurants bars grocery stores and other retail 
food establishments from using two plastics polystyrene a 
foamlike material used for cups trays and cartons and polyvinyl 
chloride used for grocery bags 
i am going to lift up my plasticfoam cup and salute the 
judges that struck down a law that would have crippled plastics 
recycling said leonard raskin a member of the consumer 
packaging coalition an industry group that opposed the law 
plastics interests challenged the law because the county hadnt 
filed an environmental impact statement 
suffolk county executive patrick g halpin said the county 
felt the benefits were obvious and therefore didnt require a 
full impact statement 
halpin said the county had yet to decide if it would appeal 
but plastics industry officials said it the law would force the 
use of more paper containers which also are slow to disintegrate 
in landfills 
switching plastics with paper was nonsense raskin said 
researchers are finding 40yearold newspapers in california 
landfills 
the laws chief sponsor legislator stephen c englebright 
noted that a state law to protect drinking water requires that all 
landfills on long island close by the end of the year 
the industry goes in with the specious argument that plastics 
are better for landfills than paper englebright said the 
ruling ignores the fact that we arent going to have landfills 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

