<TEXT>
a london newspaper reported sunday that a 
delegation of iranian officials has arrived in beirut on a mission 
to free one or more of the western hostages held in lebanon 
the independent on sunday said its information came from 
unidentified lebanese and iranian exiles in london and paris 
one exile who took part in previous hostage negotiations said 
he expected a release within days but others said a final decision 
depended on the outcome of political infighting in tehran the 
paper said 
the report follows a spate of statements from iranian newspapers 
and officials in recent days saying the hostages should be released 
because they are fueling propaganda against iran 
the independent on sunday reported the iranian team sent to 
beirut was dispatched by president hashemi rafsanjani of iran 
irans socalled pragmatists led by rafsanjani want to repair 
damaged relations with the west but they are at odds with 
hardline antiwestern radicals led by former interior minister 
ali akbar mohtashemi 
there are 18 westerners missing in lebanon most are believed 
held by proiranian factions 
the hostages include eight americans four britons two swiss 
two west germans an italian and an irishman the longest held is 
terry anderson chief middle east correspondent for the associated 
press he was kidnapped march 16 1985 
</TEXT>
