<DOCNO> AP900304-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
charles johnson faulk jr who rose from 
cub reporter to executive editor of the vicksburg evening post and 
vicksburg sunday post in a career that spanned a halfcentury died 
saturday at a hospital he was 74 
faulks career with the vicksburg newspaper began in 1935 when 
he signed on as a cub reporter over the years he was promoted to 
city editor managing editor and executive editor for the past six 
years he wrote a sunday column 
except for a stint in the navy and 10 years with the state 
highway department in the 1950s and 1960s faulk a mississippi 
native worked for the newspaper until the day his final illness 
began 
when he passed the 50year mark in the field he wrote that 
newspapering to him had been america at the grassroots the 
greatest 50 years of all time in the greatest profession of all 
time i call it life in the fast lane life on the wide screen 
three dimensional 
faulk was honored many times during his career including for 
his role as part of the newspapers team that received the pulitzer 
prize for coverage of a 1953 tornado 
he also covered the founding of local industries integration 
the mechanization of farms and the electrification of the rural 
south 
for over 50 years charlie faulk was an integral part of the 
vicksburg evening post said editor and publisher pat cashman 
charlie was both a gentle person and a gentleman a person 
from an age of graciousness and manners that are often lacking 
today his loyalty to the newspaper and his work are almost without 
comparison 
charlie was a wordsmith who excelled at his craft his writing 
could capture places events and feelings from longpast days and 
make them remarkably alive for many people cashman said 
faulk a widower is survived by a brother a sister two sons 
a daughter nine grandchildren and one greatgranddaughter 
funeral services were scheduled for monday 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

