<TEXT>
if an engraved summons to a white house state 
dinner is the ultimate badge of social power an invitation to a 
preview breakfast at the national gallery of art is the elegant 
passport to a morning spent contemplating the power of the spirit 
about 500 journalists on the gallerys mailing list are 
accustomed to opening envelopes containing glossy reproductions of 
a winslow homer watercolor a frans hals portrait or the shimmering 
pastels of an henri matisse oil painting 
these coveted invitations surely among the most beautiful ever 
dropped into a washington mailbox are sent to the reporters and 
art critics who write regularly about the dozen or more major 
exhibitions that the national gallery mounts each year 
some recipients consider the invitations themselves to be works 
of art worthy of gracing the desks walls and bulletin boards of 
newsrooms around the city 
no less admired are the buffet breakfasts served in the 
refectory the seventhfloor penthouse suite of the gallerys 
modernistic east building where the culinary theme is taken from 
the artist of the day 
at 9 oclock tuesday morning for instance about 60 journalists 
will sit down to a hearty breakfast with a dutch flavor a salute 
to the gallerys march 11 opening of an exhibition of 97 landscape 
prints and drawings by rembrandt 
the menu will include pannekoeken or dutch pancakes filled 
with spiced apples and covered with powdered sugar and fresh 
whipped cream there will be boiled sweet ham a platter of aged 
gouda edam and memolette cheeses and small raisin buns called 
krantenbollen served with butter and blackberry preserves 
if he follows the usual format gallery director j carter brown 
will introduce the curators over coffee and discuss the new show 
with his customary wit good humor and boyish enthusiasm then the 
crowd will adjourn to the rembrandt gallery for an unhurried 
preview led by experts on the 17th dutch masters work 
i cant imagine a more civilized way to begin the day said 
one press breakfast regular 
we offer culture good food and good conversation says 
gallery spokeswoman deborah ziska 
the invitations are the work of chris vogel production manager 
of the gallerys editorial office and graphics designer phyllis 
hecht based on ideas conceived by exhibition curators and public 
information specialists 
ms ziska said it takes six weeks of consultations involving as 
many as 10 gallery officials including brown before the 
invitations are printed and ready for mailing to a nationwide 
preview list of 2500 names including the local breakfast group 
we like to do something different that will catch peoples 
eyes said vogel who started using artistic images on the 
gallerys invitations in 1984 
that year for an exhibition of folding screens by western 
artists vogel used a panoramic blackandwhite photograph by ansel 
adams for the cover of an invitation in the shape of a miniature 
folding screen 
since then he and ms hecht have collaborated to produce about 
100 such invitations with images ranging from renoirs eyepopping 
odalisque a voluptuous harem beauty to an amusing 
photograph of a weather vane fish waving an american flag from the 
shelburne folk art museum in vermont 
