<TEXT>
former national security adviser john 
poindexter goes to federal court monday for what may be the last 
major trial in the irancontra scandal 
poindexter faces charges that he conspired with former white 
house aide oliver north and others inside and outside the reagan 
administration to cover up norths secret supply network to the 
contras and us involvement in a shipment of hawk missiles to iran 
reagan gave videotaped testimony for the trial last month and 
poindexters lawyers are expected to play it back in court 
poindexter is the highestranking official in the reagan white 
house to go on trial in the affair the biggest foreign policy 
debacle of ronald reagans presidency 
accused of conspiracy two counts of obstructing congress and 
two counts of making false statements poindexter could face up to 
25 years in prison and 125 million in fines if convicted 
poindexters fate will be decided by a us district court jury 
of 12 people selected from a pool of district of columbia 
residents jury selection begins monday 
irancontra prosecutor dan webb and defense attorney richard 
beckler will direct opposing teams of trial lawyers in a 
secondfloor courtroom of the us courthouse at the foot of 
capitol hill 
us district court judge harold greene will preside at the 
trial which could last up to eight weeks 
the indictment deals with poindexters assertions to congress in 
november 1986 that he didnt find out that hawk missiles had been 
shipped to iran in november 1985 until two months after the 
delivery the indictment also alleges that poindexter sent false 
letters to congress in 1986 that embraced earlier denials that 
north was assisting the contras militarily 
poindexter says his recollection of the november 1985 hawk 
shipment was very very fuzzy and that while he may have made 
incorrect statements he did not lie to congress 
my best recollection is that i did not remember anything 
about or know anything about the hawks until january 86 
poindexter told congressional investigators in immunized testimony 
in 1987 
the ciaassisted november 1985 shipment of hawks was authorized 
retroactively by a presidential finding which poindexter presented 
to reagan for signing after the weapons were delivered the 
politically embarrassing finding depicted the transaction with iran 
as straight armsforhostages trade poindexter destroyed the 
document hours after he told his alleged lies to congress 
former cia director william casey testified the same day 
telling members of the house and senate intelligence committees the 
cia had been told the cargo consisted of spare parts for oil 
drilling fields in iran casey gave no indication the cia and 
national security council staff knew that the shipment was arms 
in connection with the contra portion of the indictment reagan 
gave testimony that was favorable to poindexter reagan said i am 
in total agreement and in complete support of letters 
poindexter sent to congress 
poindexters letters endorsed information national security 
adviser robert mcfarlane gave congress in 1985 denying that north 
was raising money or providing military advice to the nicaraguan 
rebels mcfarlane subsequently pleaded guilty to crimes in 
connection with the information he had provided in letters to 
congress 
reagan said he hadnt known mcfarlane had pleaded guilty in 
connection with the letters and said he didnt know the tower 
commission which he appointed had concluded north was assisting the 
contras militarily 
in his videotaped testimony the former president said he didnt 
think poindexter had made any false statements in the irancontra 
affair 
in addition reagan suggested it might have been all right in 
november 1986 as the irancontra affair was unfolding to destroy 
documents and withhold information from congress that body 
explained reagan habitually leaked sensitive information that in 
this instance might have jeopardized the lives of us hostages 
held in lebanon 
part of the conspiracy charge accuses poindexter of working with 
north to destroy classified documents and records of the national 
security council 
north was convicted by a jury last may of three felonies in the 
irancontra scandal sentenced to 1200 hours of community service 
fined 150000 and given two years probation 
one of the crimes for which north was convicted aiding and 
abetting an obstruction of congress involved the november 1985 
shipment of hawks for which poindexter is now charged 
north is appealing the convictions and the fine while performing 
the community service in an antidrug program 
richard secord and albert hakim businessmen who assisted north 
in supplying the contras and ship arms to iran pleaded guilty to 
crimes in the irancontra affair and were placed on probation 
businessmen carl channell and richard miller who raised private 
donations for the contras pleaded guilty to conspiring to defraud 
the government of taxes and were placed on probation 
the bush administration stepped in and blocked the use of some 
classified material in the case of joseph fernandez the former cia 
station chief in costa rica as a result of the action by attorney 
general dick thornburgh the judge in the case dismissed charges 
that fernandez lied about his assistance to norths contra resupply 
network irancontra prosecutors are appealing 
thomas clines a former cia agent who assisted north in locating 
sources of arms and shipping them to the contras is under 
indictment for alleged tax violations in the scandal and is 
scheduled to appear in federal court in baltimore later this month 
